aas:langStringTextType.aas:text: For Catena-X(CX) business case Quality Management. Supported technical features: delta update feature, meta information feature and additionalInformationList key-value pairs. The supported model features are described in detail in the Catena-X Quality KIT. This model is used to exchange claim information. FleetClaim data model is used to exchange a list of claims. A Claim is a complaint of a vehicle owner. The assumption for this data model is that a customer is coming to a repair shop and complaining about a malfunction in his/her vehicle during vehicle's warranty period. The repair shop than diagnosis the car (this is the link to FleetDiagnostic data model) and can eventually exchange faulty parts. The repair shop later hands in the invoice to the OEM to compensate his work. Defining the uniqueness of a claim: A claim gets a unique claimId (unique within one OEM). A claim is related to one vehicle that can be identified by anonymizedVIN and refers to a potentially faulty part/component in the vehicle. A claim is coming from a specific country - this is normally the country of the repair shop. A claim can contain a list of replaced parts that were put out of the affected vehicle and a list of spare parts/new parts that were put into the affected vehicle. Some of the old, potentially faulty parts are send back to the part's manufacturer for detailed analyses (this is the link to the PartsAnalyses data model).
A list of customer complaints or workshop repairs that belong to one or more quality tasks.
A list of customer complaints or workshop repairs that belong to one or more quality tasks.
A list of diagnostic sessions linked to this claim.
A list of diagnostic sessions linked to this claim.
A list of claimed parts which were replaced or repaired.

A list of spare parts that were built into the vehicle.

Vehicle manufacturer-specific anonymized VIN, which is still a unique identifier within this data provider.
A unique quality task identifier within this data-space.
Country code in ISO 3166-1 alpha-3 codes where this session took place
Each claim from this data provider has a unique claim ID.If you combine the BPNL of the data provider with this claim ID you get a unique claim ID in the data space.
References the date when the claim was initially reported.
The mileage counter of the vehicle when it was in the workshop.
The unit of the repair mileage - either km or mi. Default is km.
A unique identifier for this vehicle in data-space. This property is optional as of now not all vehicles have this identifier assigned.

The record operation enumeration can be used to realize delta update concept. An example using scenario that data delivery runs weekly: Week0: All data is transferred -> all rows have recordStatus=new. Week1: Only the changed data is transferred: That means new rows, or updated or deleted rows: New rows get recordStatus=new, changed rows get recordStatus=changed and deleted/removed rows get recordStatus=deleted.
End customer comment (e.g. from the vehicle owner, rental car user, etc. ) about the malfunction of this vehicle.
OEM-specific damage code
Description of the damage code.
Short description of the claim from the technicians

A unique identifier for a workshop. This identifier is unique within data provider's company. If you combine this identifier with BPNL from data provider than you get a unique identifier for this workshop in this data space.
Latitude property for GPS coordinates.
Longitude property for GPS coordinates.
Groups workshop-related properties
A unique identifier for a session. If you combine the session property with BPNL of data provider than you get a unique identifier for this session in this data-space.
A list of diagnostic sessions linked to this claim.
Flag is set to true if part was causing the problem-otherwise false.
Flag is set to true if part was replaced-otherwise false.
Counter for non-serial parts which have been replaced
Describes what happened to this part in the claim.
The name of a part. A part name is not unique - same kinds of parts can have the same part name.
A textual description of the part.

Often vehicle manufacturer specific: An assembly part number version. Assembly parts are often produced by a supplier that combines his own parts with other parts from other suppliers and ships as one assembly to a vehicle manufacturer.
A batch number describes all parts that were manufactured in the same run.
Calibration for this ECU. This could be the result of a calibration process.
A unique part identifier in this data-space. Property is optional as of now not all parts have this identifier.

String that is encoded in a data matrix code. Data matrix codes or short DMC are labelled/printed on parts. Example: A data matrix code can combine supplier name, part type, manufacturing and many more information. A DMC string is often unique within this data provider.
The delivery note of a package. A delivery note is unique within one logistics company.
The hardware version of this part.
The order number of this order. This is a unique identifier defined by the supplier of the order. If you combine order number and BPNL of the supplier you get a unique identifier in this data-space.
The number of a physical part. A part number is not unique - same kinds of parts can have same part numbers. Part numbers and part description normally relate to each other.
The version of this hardware part.

Serial number of one specific part. A serial number is unique within one company. If you combine serial number with BPNL of that company than you get a unique identifier for this part in this data-space.
Software number installed in this electronic control unit.
Software version installed in this electronic control unit.

An electronic control unit has many parameters that have to be set to work correctly: Examples are target market (which functions need to be activated for the target market) or the equipment of the vehicle (e.g. navigation system is installed).
A list of claimed parts which were replaced or repaired.

A unique identifier for one supplier inside data provider's company. If you combine supplier ID with BPNL of data provider you get a unique identifier for this supplier in this data space. As an alternative you can use BPNL to identify a supplier.
The name of one supplier company.
A list of spare parts that were built into the vehicle.
